{"entries":[{"stem":"backward-cache-key-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/backward-cache-key-v1.yaml","description":"Provable contract: backward kernel cache keys must be unique per kernel. Root cause of cuBLAS loss=0.0: warm! macro used hardcoded \"silu_backward\" for ALL kernel cache keys, causing wrong kernel to be loaded at runtime. Five-whys traced from loss=0.0 → CUDA context poisoned → silu_backward JIT failure → cache key collision → copy-paste bug in warm! macro.","equations":["cache_key_uniqueness"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Each kernel type maps to a distinct cache key","warm! macro uses $key parameter, not hardcoded string"],"references":["trueno#200 — silu_backward PTX fails on Blackwell","entrenar#300 — ENT-287 cuBLAS integration","GH-480 — Blackwell backward branch JIT bug"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":2,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"backward-cache-key-v1 Provable contract: backward kernel cache keys must be unique per kernel. Root cause of cuBLAS loss=0.0: warm! macro used hardcoded \"silu_backward\" for ALL kernel cache keys, causing wrong kernel to be loaded at runtime. Five-whys traced from loss=0.0 → CUDA context poisoned → silu_backward JIT failure → cache key collision → copy-paste bug in warm! macro. cache_key_uniqueness forall k1, k2 in KernelSet: k1 != k2 => cache_key(k1) != cache_key(k2) Each kernel type maps to a distinct cache key warm! macro uses $key parameter, not hardcoded string Each kernel type maps to a distinct cache key Each kernel type maps to a distinct cache key warm! macro uses $key parameter, not hardcoded string warm! macro uses $key parameter, not hardcoded string trueno#200 — silu_backward PTX fails on Blackwell entrenar#300 — ENT-287 cuBLAS integration GH-480 — Blackwell backward branch JIT bug"},{"stem":"benchmark-expansion-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/benchmark-expansion-v1.yaml","description":"ShellSafetyBench expansion generator (PMAT-176) produces valid, deterministic, linter-consistent labeled entries for Bash, Makefile, and Dockerfile formats.","equations":["expansion_balance"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Both safe and unsafe labels present for each format","Same seed produces identical output"],"references":["SSC v12 Phase 9 #10: Expand ShellSafetyBench to 50K+ entries"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":7,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"benchmark-expansion-v1 ShellSafetyBench expansion generator (PMAT-176) produces valid, deterministic, linter-consistent labeled entries for Bash, Makefile, and Dockerfile formats. expansion_balance forall fmt in {Bash, Makefile, Dockerfile}: safe_count(expand(fmt, n, seed)) > 0 AND unsafe_count(expand(fmt, n, seed)) > 0 Both safe and unsafe labels present for each format Same seed produces identical output Both safe and unsafe labels present for each format Both safe and unsafe labels present for each format Same seed produces identical output Same seed produces identical output SSC v12 Phase 9 #10: Expand ShellSafetyBench to 50K+ entries"},{"stem":"bidirectional-attention-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/bidirectional-attention-v1.yaml","description":"Bidirectional (encoder) attention — full attention without causal mask","equations":["bidirectional_attention"],"obligation_types":["equivalence","invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Causal parity on single-token input","Full attention density","Weight normalization"],"references":["Devlin et al. (2019) BERT: Pre-training of Deep Bidirectional Transformers"],"depends_on":["attention-kernel-v1","softmax-kernel-v1"],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":3,"falsification_count":3,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"bidirectional-attention-v1 Bidirectional (encoder) attention — full attention without causal mask bidirectional_attention BiAttn(Q, K, V) = softmax(QK^T / sqrt(d_k)) * V Every token attends to every other token (no mask) Attention weights are dense (no structural zeros) Equivalent to causal attention when n=1 Causal parity on single-token input |BiAttn(q, k, v) - CausalAttn(q, k, v)| < eps for n=1 Full attention density attn_weights[i][j] > 0 for all i, j in 0..n Weight normalization sum_j(attn_weights[i][j]) = 1 for all i Devlin et al. (2019) BERT: Pre-training of Deep Bidirectional Transformers"},{"stem":"chat-inference-pipeline-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/chat-inference-pipeline-v1.yaml","description":"Chat model inference pipeline — Qwen-1.5B + LoRA for shell safety explanation and fix generation","equations":["autoregressive_generation","chat_template","sampling"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant","invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Generation terminates","Valid token range","Greedy determinism","Graceful fallback"],"references":["SSC v11 spec Section 8.1, Phase 4 CLI-002","Hu et al. (2021) LoRA: Low-Rank Adaptation of Large Language Models"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":4,"falsification_count":5,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"chat-inference-pipeline-v1 Chat model inference pipeline — Qwen-1.5B + LoRA for shell safety explanation and fix generation autoregressive_generation P(y_t | y_{<t}, x) = softmax(W_h @ h_t + b) Generated sequence length <= max_new_tokens Each token sampled from valid vocabulary range EOS token terminates generation chat_template prompt = <|im_start|>system\\n{system}<|im_end|>\\n<|im_start|>user\\n{user}<|im_end|>\\n<|im_start|>assistant\\n System prompt always includes safety analysis context User message contains the script and linter findings sampling token = argmax(logits) if T=0, else sample(softmax(logits/T), top_k) T=0 always produces argmax (deterministic) top_k=1 always produces argmax Sampled token always in valid vocabulary range Generation terminates len(output) <= max_new_tokens for all inputs Valid token range 0 <= token_id < vocab_size for all generated tokens Greedy determinism generate(x, T=0) == generate(x, T=0) for same model weights Graceful fallback Without ml feature, chat_generate returns informative error SSC v11 spec Section 8.1, Phase 4 CLI-002 Hu et al. (2021) LoRA: Low-Rank Adaptation of Large Language Models"},{"stem":"chat-model-training-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/chat-model-training-v1.yaml","description":"Chat model training — Qwen2.5-Coder-0.5B-Instruct LoRA fine-tuning on shell safety conversations","equations":["chat_loss","lora_forward"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Base weights W_0 are frozen (no gradient updates)","Only A, B matrices receive gradients","Effective rank << min(d_in, d_out)"],"references":["Hu et al. (2021) LoRA: Low-Rank Adaptation of Large Language Models","SSC v11 Section 7: Chat Model Fine-Tuning"],"depends_on":["classifier-pipeline-v1","chat-inference-pipeline-v1"],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":3,"falsification_count":4,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"chat-model-training-v1 Chat model training — Qwen2.5-Coder-0.5B-Instruct LoRA fine-tuning on shell safety conversations chat_loss L = -sum_t log P(y_t | y_{<t}, x) for response tokens only Loss computed only on assistant response tokens (not system/user) Cross-entropy with teacher forcing lora_forward h = W_0 @ x + (alpha/rank) * B @ A @ x Base weights W_0 are frozen (no gradient updates) Only A, B matrices receive gradients Effective rank << min(d_in, d_out) Base weights W_0 are frozen (no gradient updates) Base weights W_0 are frozen (no gradient updates) Only A, B matrices receive gradients Only A, B matrices receive gradients Effective rank << min(d_in, d_out) Effective rank << min(d_in, d_out) Hu et al. (2021) LoRA: Low-Rank Adaptation of Large Language Models SSC v11 Section 7: Chat Model Fine-Tuning"},{"stem":"cpu-gpu-forward-parity-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/cpu-gpu-forward-parity-v1.yaml","description":"CPU/GPU transformer block forward pass parity — same input must produce same output","equations":["cpu_forward","gpu_forward"],"obligation_types":["equivalence","invariant","invariant","invariant","bound"],"properties":["CPU/GPU forward parity","RoPE applied on both paths","QK-norm applied on both paths","Operation ordering","NF4 quantization error"],"references":["entrenar#270: CUDA forward path missing RoPE and QK-norm","ENT-269: matmul_nt fix for HF weight transpose","Vaswani et al. (2017) Attention Is All You Need","Su et al. (2021) RoFormer: Enhanced Transformer with Rotary Position Embedding"],"depends_on":["encoder-forward-v1"],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":5,"falsification_count":6,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"cpu-gpu-forward-parity-v1 CPU/GPU transformer block forward pass parity — same input must produce same output cpu_forward h = RMSNorm(x)\nQ = h @ W_q^T + LoRA_q(h)\nK = h @ W_k^T\nV = h @ W_v^T + LoRA_v(h)\nQ = QK_Norm(Q)\nK = QK_Norm(K)\nQ = RoPE(Q, pos)\nK = RoPE(K, pos)\nattn = softmax(Q @ K^T / sqrt(d_k)) @ V\nout = x + attn @ W_o^T\n RoPE provides positional information QK-norm stabilizes attention magnitudes gpu_forward h = RMSNorm_GPU(x)\nQ = NF4_GEMM(h, W_q_nf4) + LoRA_q_GPU(h)\nK = NF4_GEMM(h, W_k_nf4)\nV = NF4_GEMM(h, W_v_nf4) + LoRA_v_GPU(h)\nQ = QK_Norm_GPU(Q)      # MISSING (entrenar#270)\nK = QK_Norm_GPU(K)      # MISSING (entrenar#270)\nQ = RoPE_GPU(Q, pos)    # MISSING (entrenar#270)\nK = RoPE_GPU(K, pos)    # MISSING (entrenar#270)\nattn = softmax(Q @ K^T / sqrt(d_k)) @ V\nout = x + NF4_GEMM(attn, W_o_nf4)\n Must apply same operations as CPU path NF4 quantization introduces bounded error (C-NF4-003) CPU/GPU forward parity |cpu_forward(x, pos) - gpu_forward(x, pos)| < tolerance for all x, pos RoPE applied on both paths cpu_forward applies RoPE iff gpu_forward applies RoPE QK-norm applied on both paths cpu_forward applies QK-norm iff gpu_forward applies QK-norm Operation ordering Both paths apply operations in order: projection → QK-norm → RoPE → attention NF4 quantization error |gpu_gemm(A, dequant(Q_nf4)) - cpu_matmul_nt(A, W)| < 1e-3 per element entrenar#270: CUDA forward path missing RoPE and QK-norm ENT-269: matmul_nt fix for HF weight transpose Vaswani et al. (2017) Attention Is All You Need Su et al. (2021) RoFormer: Enhanced Transformer with Rotary Position Embedding"},{"stem":"dimension-independent-kernels-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/dimension-independent-kernels-v1.yaml","description":"Provable contract for trueno kernel architecture: all GPU kernels must be dimension-independent (pass M/K/N as runtime params, not baked into PTX). This eliminates JIT compilation during training and the Blackwell context poisoning bug (trueno#200). See S18.14.","equations":["dimension_independence"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Kernel works for any power-of-2 dimension","Output shape matches input shape"],"references":["trueno#200 — Blackwell cuModuleLoadData fails during active GPU work","S18.10 — 8 training failures from JIT during GPU work","S18.13 — ELI5: PyTorch ships pre-compiled, we JIT-compile"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":5,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"dimension-independent-kernels-v1 Provable contract for trueno kernel architecture: all GPU kernels must be dimension-independent (pass M/K/N as runtime params, not baked into PTX). This eliminates JIT compilation during training and the Blackwell context poisoning bug (trueno#200). See S18.14. dimension_independence forall d in {128, 256, 512, 1024}: kernel(x, d) produces valid output Kernel works for any power-of-2 dimension Output shape matches input shape Kernel works for any power-of-2 dimension Kernel works for any power-of-2 dimension Output shape matches input shape Output shape matches input shape trueno#200 — Blackwell cuModuleLoadData fails during active GPU work S18.10 — 8 training failures from JIT during GPU work S18.13 — ELI5: PyTorch ships pre-compiled, we JIT-compile"},{"stem":"encoder-forward-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/encoder-forward-v1.yaml","description":"Encoder forward pass — full pipeline from tokens to [CLS] embedding","equations":["cls_pooling","encoder_layer"],"obligation_types":["invariant","bound","equivalence"],"properties":["Shape preservation","No NaN/Inf","Reference parity"],"references":["Devlin et al. (2019) BERT","Liu et al. (2019) RoBERTa"],"depends_on":["bidirectional-attention-v1","learned-position-embedding-v1","layernorm-kernel-v1","gelu-kernel-v1"],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":3,"falsification_count":3,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"encoder-forward-v1 Encoder forward pass — full pipeline from tokens to [CLS] embedding cls_pooling embedding = encoder_output[0]  (first token) encoder_layer h = LayerNorm(x + BiAttn(x)) ; out = LayerNorm(h + FFN(h)) Output shape equals input shape (residual connection preserves dimensions) No NaN or Inf in output for finite input Shape preservation output.shape == input.shape for each encoder layer No NaN/Inf is_finite(output[i][j]) for all i, j Reference parity |entrenar_output - reference_output| < tolerance Devlin et al. (2019) BERT Liu et al. (2019) RoBERTa"},{"stem":"encoder-roundtrip-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/encoder-roundtrip-v1.yaml","description":"Provable escape function contracts (GH-183). The escape functions are the #1 defense against shell injection in emitted code. Every special character must be neutralized. A single unescaped metachar falsifies the contract.","equations":["escape_roundtrip"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Shell metacharacters ($, `, |, ;) are always neutralized","Empty strings produce valid shell output"],"references":["GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts","CWE-78: OS Command Injection","binding.yaml: encoder-roundtrip-v1 (5 bindings)"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":14,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"encoder-roundtrip-v1 Provable escape function contracts (GH-183). The escape functions are the #1 defense against shell injection in emitted code. Every special character must be neutralized. A single unescaped metachar falsifies the contract. escape_roundtrip escape(escape(s)) == escape(s) (idempotent) Shell metacharacters ($, `, |, ;) are always neutralized Empty strings produce valid shell output Shell metacharacters ($, `, |, ;) are always neutralized Shell metacharacters ($, `, |, ;) are always neutralized Empty strings produce valid shell output Empty strings produce valid shell output GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts CWE-78: OS Command Injection binding.yaml: encoder-roundtrip-v1 (5 bindings)"},{"stem":"hf-publish-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/hf-publish-v1.yaml","description":"HuggingFace benchmark publication (PMAT-172) generates a complete, valid dataset repository with proper metadata and split files.","equations":["dataset_integrity"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["All splits present and non-empty","Model card contains required fields"],"references":["SSC v12 Phase 10: Export + publish to HuggingFace","HuggingFace Datasets documentation"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":8,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"hf-publish-v1 HuggingFace benchmark publication (PMAT-172) generates a complete, valid dataset repository with proper metadata and split files. dataset_integrity published_dataset == local_export (byte-identical after decompression) All splits present and non-empty Model card contains required fields All splits present and non-empty All splits present and non-empty Model card contains required fields Model card contains required fields SSC v12 Phase 10: Export + publish to HuggingFace HuggingFace Datasets documentation"},{"stem":"learned-position-embedding-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/learned-position-embedding-v1.yaml","description":"Learned absolute position embeddings (RoBERTa-style)","equations":["position_embedding"],"obligation_types":["bound","equivalence"],"properties":["Position in range","Deterministic lookup"],"references":["Liu et al. (2019) RoBERTa: A Robustly Optimized BERT Pretraining Approach"],"depends_on":["embedding-lookup-v1"],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":2,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"learned-position-embedding-v1 Learned absolute position embeddings (RoBERTa-style) position_embedding PE(pos) = E[pos] where E in R^{max_positions x d_model} Lookup is O(1) (table index, not computation) pos < max_positions (bounds check) Position in range 0 <= pos < max_positions Deterministic lookup PE(pos) = PE(pos) for same weights (idempotent) Liu et al. (2019) RoBERTa: A Robustly Optimized BERT Pretraining Approach"},{"stem":"linear-probe-classifier-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/linear-probe-classifier-v1.yaml","description":"Linear probe classifier — frozen encoder + trained linear head","equations":["linear_probe"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Encoder frozen","Probability simplex","Embedding determinism"],"references":["Alain & Bengio (2016) Understanding intermediate layers using linear classifier probes"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":3,"falsification_count":3,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"linear-probe-classifier-v1 Linear probe classifier — frozen encoder + trained linear head linear_probe logits = W @ embedding + b ; probs = softmax(logits) Frozen encoder weights do not receive gradients Only W and b are updated during training probs sum to 1.0 Encoder frozen encoder_params_before == encoder_params_after for each training step Probability simplex |sum(probs) - 1.0| < eps AND probs_i > 0 for all i Embedding determinism embed(x) == embed(x) for same x and weights (bit-identical) Alain & Bengio (2016) Understanding intermediate layers using linear classifier probes"},{"stem":"lint-perf-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/lint-perf-v1.yaml","description":"Lint performance contract (PMAT-226). Verifies that bashrs lint --time reports lint latency, that the lint engine scales sub-linearly with script size, and that incremental lint cost per 50 lines is under 100ms in debug mode (under 10ms in release).","equations":["lint_latency"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Sub-linear scaling: 20x lines < 5x latency","Incremental lint cost < 10ms per 50 lines"],"references":["PMAT-226: PERF-10MS Sprint 14","docs/specifications/world-class-bash-linter-spec.md"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":7,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"lint-perf-v1 Lint performance contract (PMAT-226). Verifies that bashrs lint --time reports lint latency, that the lint engine scales sub-linearly with script size, and that incremental lint cost per 50 lines is under 100ms in debug mode (under 10ms in release). lint_latency lint_time(script, n_lines) < 10ms for n_lines <= 50 Sub-linear scaling: 20x lines < 5x latency Incremental lint cost < 10ms per 50 lines Sub-linear scaling: 20x lines < 5x latency Sub-linear scaling: 20x lines < 5x latency Incremental lint cost < 10ms per 50 lines Incremental lint cost < 10ms per 50 lines PMAT-226: PERF-10MS Sprint 14 docs/specifications/world-class-bash-linter-spec.md"},{"stem":"linter-coverage-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/linter-coverage-v1.yaml","description":"Linter rule coverage contract (GAP-4). Verifies that each linter rule category fires on at least one known-bad input per applicable format. A rule that never fires is dead code. A format without coverage is an untested surface. Both falsify this contract.","equations":["rule_coverage"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Every active rule fires on at least one corpus entry","No orphan rules without test coverage"],"references":["SSC v13 Section 3 GAP-4: linter coverage","GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":6,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"linter-coverage-v1 Linter rule coverage contract (GAP-4). Verifies that each linter rule category fires on at least one known-bad input per applicable format. A rule that never fires is dead code. A format without coverage is an untested surface. Both falsify this contract. rule_coverage forall rule in RuleSet(fmt): exists entry in Corpus(fmt): fires(rule, entry) Every active rule fires on at least one corpus entry No orphan rules without test coverage Every active rule fires on at least one corpus entry Every active rule fires on at least one corpus entry No orphan rules without test coverage No orphan rules without test coverage SSC v13 Section 3 GAP-4: linter coverage GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts"},{"stem":"linter-det-idem-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/linter-det-idem-v1.yaml","description":"Provable determinism and idempotency linter contracts (GH-183). DET rules detect non-deterministic constructs ($RANDOM, timestamps, unordered globs, system state). IDEM rules detect non-idempotent operations (mkdir without -p, rm without -f, ln without -sf). Each rule must detect known-bad and not false-positive on known-safe.","equations":["determinism_detection"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["DET rules detect all non-deterministic constructs","DET rules do NOT false-positive on deterministic code"],"references":["GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts","CLAUDE.md: Critical Invariants — Determinism + Idempotency"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":14,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"linter-det-idem-v1 Provable determinism and idempotency linter contracts (GH-183). DET rules detect non-deterministic constructs ($RANDOM, timestamps, unordered globs, system state). IDEM rules detect non-idempotent operations (mkdir without -p, rm without -f, ln without -sf). Each rule must detect known-bad and not false-positive on known-safe. determinism_detection forall s in NonDeterministic: exists rule in DET: fires(rule, s) DET rules detect all non-deterministic constructs DET rules do NOT false-positive on deterministic code DET rules detect all non-deterministic constructs DET rules detect all non-deterministic constructs DET rules do NOT false-positive on deterministic code DET rules do NOT false-positive on deterministic code GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts CLAUDE.md: Critical Invariants — Determinism + Idempotency"},{"stem":"linter-docker-make-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/linter-docker-make-v1.yaml","description":"Provable Dockerfile and Makefile linter contracts (GH-183). DOCKER rules detect container security/quality issues. MAKE rules detect non-deterministic, non-idempotent, and unsafe patterns. Each rule must detect known-bad and not false-positive on known-safe.","equations":["multi_format_linting"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Dockerfile rules fire on known-bad Dockerfiles","Makefile rules fire on known-bad Makefiles"],"references":["GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts","hadolint best practices (DOCKER rules)"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":12,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"linter-docker-make-v1 Provable Dockerfile and Makefile linter contracts (GH-183). DOCKER rules detect container security/quality issues. MAKE rules detect non-deterministic, non-idempotent, and unsafe patterns. Each rule must detect known-bad and not false-positive on known-safe. multi_format_linting lint(file, fmt) produces diagnostics where fmt in {Dockerfile, Makefile} Dockerfile rules fire on known-bad Dockerfiles Makefile rules fire on known-bad Makefiles Dockerfile rules fire on known-bad Dockerfiles Dockerfile rules fire on known-bad Dockerfiles Makefile rules fire on known-bad Makefiles Makefile rules fire on known-bad Makefiles GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts hadolint best practices (DOCKER rules)"},{"stem":"linter-security-rules-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/linter-security-rules-v1.yaml","description":"Provable security rule contracts (GH-183). Each SEC rule must detect known-vulnerable patterns (soundness) and not flag known-safe patterns (precision). A single missed detection or false positive falsifies the contract.","equations":["security_detection"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["SEC rules detect all OWASP-class vulnerabilities","SEC rules do NOT false-positive on safe code"],"references":["GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts","OWASP Command Injection","CWE-78: OS Command Injection","CWE-798: Hardcoded Credentials"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":16,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"linter-security-rules-v1 Provable security rule contracts (GH-183). Each SEC rule must detect known-vulnerable patterns (soundness) and not flag known-safe patterns (precision). A single missed detection or false positive falsifies the contract. security_detection forall s in Vulnerable: exists rule in SEC: fires(rule, s) SEC rules detect all OWASP-class vulnerabilities SEC rules do NOT false-positive on safe code SEC rules detect all OWASP-class vulnerabilities SEC rules detect all OWASP-class vulnerabilities SEC rules do NOT false-positive on safe code SEC rules do NOT false-positive on safe code GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts OWASP Command Injection CWE-78: OS Command Injection CWE-798: Hardcoded Credentials"},{"stem":"mcdc-coverage-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/mcdc-coverage-v1.yaml","description":"MC/DC (Modified Condition/Decision Coverage) analysis contract (PMAT-224). Verifies that bashrs coverage --mcdc correctly decomposes compound conditions (&&, ||, -a, -o) into individual sub-conditions and reports the minimum number of test pairs needed for full MC/DC coverage. Supports [[ ]], [ ], test builtin, if/while/elif guards, and both terminal and JSON output formats.","equations":["mcdc_decomposition"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Each condition is independently testable","Required test pairs satisfy MC/DC criterion"],"references":["PMAT-224: MCDC Sprint 10","docs/specifications/world-class-bash-linter-spec.md"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":11,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"mcdc-coverage-v1 MC/DC (Modified Condition/Decision Coverage) analysis contract (PMAT-224). Verifies that bashrs coverage --mcdc correctly decomposes compound conditions (&&, ||, -a, -o) into individual sub-conditions and reports the minimum number of test pairs needed for full MC/DC coverage. Supports [[ ]], [ ], test builtin, if/while/elif guards, and both terminal and JSON output formats. mcdc_decomposition mcdc(decision) = {conditions} where each condition independently affects decision outcome Each condition is independently testable Required test pairs satisfy MC/DC criterion Each condition is independently testable Each condition is independently testable Required test pairs satisfy MC/DC criterion Required test pairs satisfy MC/DC criterion PMAT-224: MCDC Sprint 10 docs/specifications/world-class-bash-linter-spec.md"},{"stem":"nf4-codebook-parity-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/nf4-codebook-parity-v1.yaml","description":"Falsification contract: verify trueno NF4 codebook mapping matches bitsandbytes. Root cause of 3.64 loss gap at step 1 (15.50 vs 11.86). See trueno#195, ENT-285, arXiv:2305.14314 (QLoRA, Dettmers et al. 2023).","equations":["nf4_quantization"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Codebook matches reference NormalFloat4 values","Quantization error bounded by max bin width"],"references":["arXiv:2305.14314 — QLoRA: Efficient Finetuning of Quantized LLMs","trueno#195 — NF4 codebook mapping incompatible with bitsandbytes","entrenar#298 — NF4 weight loading uses wrong codebook mapping"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":5,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"nf4-codebook-parity-v1 Falsification contract: verify trueno NF4 codebook mapping matches bitsandbytes. Root cause of 3.64 loss gap at step 1 (15.50 vs 11.86). See trueno#195, ENT-285, arXiv:2305.14314 (QLoRA, Dettmers et al. 2023). nf4_quantization dequant(quant(x, codebook), codebook) ~= x within tolerance Codebook matches reference NormalFloat4 values Quantization error bounded by max bin width Codebook matches reference NormalFloat4 values Codebook matches reference NormalFloat4 values Quantization error bounded by max bin width Quantization error bounded by max bin width arXiv:2305.14314 — QLoRA: Efficient Finetuning of Quantized LLMs trueno#195 — NF4 codebook mapping incompatible with bitsandbytes entrenar#298 — NF4 weight loading uses wrong codebook mapping"},{"stem":"nf4-cublas-parity-v2","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/nf4-cublas-parity-v2.yaml","description":"Falsification contract for NF4 cuBLAS GEMM parity (ENT-287). Five cuBLAS integration attempts produced loss=0.0. This contract isolates the failure to a SINGLE projection GEMM, not the full model. Source: bitsandbytes csrc/kernels.cu (NF4 dequant + matmul4bit).","equations":["cublas_parity"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["NF4 GEMM matches dequantized f32 GEMM within tolerance","Performance >= 2x speedup vs f32"],"references":["bitsandbytes csrc/kernels.cu:520-521 — NF4 nibble order (HIGH then LOW)","bitsandbytes autograd/_functions.py:320 — dequant().to(dtype).t() then linear","trueno nf4_cpu.rs:173-174 — LOW then HIGH (opposite of bnb)","arXiv:2305.14314 — QLoRA","entrenar#300 — ENT-287 cuBLAS integration"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":5,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"nf4-cublas-parity-v2 Falsification contract for NF4 cuBLAS GEMM parity (ENT-287). Five cuBLAS integration attempts produced loss=0.0. This contract isolates the failure to a SINGLE projection GEMM, not the full model. Source: bitsandbytes csrc/kernels.cu (NF4 dequant + matmul4bit). cublas_parity |nf4_gemm(A, B) - f32_gemm(dequant(A), B)| < tolerance NF4 GEMM matches dequantized f32 GEMM within tolerance Performance >= 2x speedup vs f32 NF4 GEMM matches dequantized f32 GEMM within tolerance NF4 GEMM matches dequantized f32 GEMM within tolerance Performance >= 2x speedup vs f32 Performance >= 2x speedup vs f32 bitsandbytes csrc/kernels.cu:520-521 — NF4 nibble order (HIGH then LOW) bitsandbytes autograd/_functions.py:320 — dequant().to(dtype).t() then linear trueno nf4_cpu.rs:173-174 — LOW then HIGH (opposite of bnb) arXiv:2305.14314 — QLoRA entrenar#300 — ENT-287 cuBLAS integration"},{"stem":"nf4-cublas-throughput-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/nf4-cublas-throughput-v1.yaml","description":"Provable contract for NF4 two-pass dequant+cuBLAS GEMM (ENT-286). Verifies that the cuBLAS path produces identical results to the fused NF4 kernel while achieving >10x throughput improvement. See entrenar#299, trueno#187, arXiv:2305.14314 §3.1.","equations":["throughput_baseline"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Throughput meets baseline for each matrix size","No regression vs previous version"],"references":["arXiv:2305.14314 — QLoRA §3.1: dequantization strategy","entrenar#299 — 74x throughput gap","trueno#187 — NF4 GEMM optimization"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":5,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"nf4-cublas-throughput-v1 Provable contract for NF4 two-pass dequant+cuBLAS GEMM (ENT-286). Verifies that the cuBLAS path produces identical results to the fused NF4 kernel while achieving >10x throughput improvement. See entrenar#299, trueno#187, arXiv:2305.14314 §3.1. throughput_baseline throughput(nf4_gemm) >= target_tflops for given matrix dimensions Throughput meets baseline for each matrix size No regression vs previous version Throughput meets baseline for each matrix size Throughput meets baseline for each matrix size No regression vs previous version No regression vs previous version arXiv:2305.14314 — QLoRA §3.1: dequantization strategy entrenar#299 — 74x throughput gap trueno#187 — NF4 GEMM optimization"},{"stem":"parser-soundness-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/parser-soundness-v1.yaml","description":"Provable parser soundness contracts (GH-183). The bash parser must correctly lex, parse, and produce ASTs for valid bash. It must not silently drop constructs. Parse must be deterministic.","equations":["parse_soundness"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Valid bash always parses without error","Roundtrip preserves semantic meaning"],"references":["GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts","binding.yaml: parser-soundness-v1 (3 bindings: lex, parse, semantic)"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":12,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"parser-soundness-v1 Provable parser soundness contracts (GH-183). The bash parser must correctly lex, parse, and produce ASTs for valid bash. It must not silently drop constructs. Parse must be deterministic. parse_soundness forall valid_bash s: parse(s) != Error AND emit(parse(s)) ~= s Valid bash always parses without error Roundtrip preserves semantic meaning Valid bash always parses without error Valid bash always parses without error Roundtrip preserves semantic meaning Roundtrip preserves semantic meaning GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts binding.yaml: parser-soundness-v1 (3 bindings: lex, parse, semantic)"},{"stem":"probar-shell-safety-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/probar-shell-safety-v1.yaml","description":"Probar test suite contract for SSC v11 Phase 6.\nVerifies WASM linter/classifier correctness, determinism,\nand performance budgets via Layer 1 (logic) and Layer 3 (perf) tests.","equations":["safety_classification"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Safe scripts produce safe classification","Scripts with eval/injection produce unsafe classification"],"references":["docs/specifications/shell-safety-inference.md"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":9,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"probar-shell-safety-v1 Probar test suite contract for SSC v11 Phase 6.\nVerifies WASM linter/classifier correctness, determinism,\nand performance budgets via Layer 1 (logic) and Layer 3 (perf) tests. safety_classification classify(s) in {safe, unsafe} with confidence in [10, 95] Safe scripts produce safe classification Scripts with eval/injection produce unsafe classification Safe scripts produce safe classification Safe scripts produce safe classification Scripts with eval/injection produce unsafe classification Scripts with eval/injection produce unsafe classification docs/specifications/shell-safety-inference.md"},{"stem":"property-dsl-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/property-dsl-v1.yaml","description":"Property definition DSL contract (PMAT-225). Verifies that bashrs property --custom loads user-defined property checks from TOML files. The DSL supports forbid rules (regex patterns that are violations when matched) and require rules (patterns that must match at least one line). Custom properties integrate with built-in properties in both terminal and JSON output.","equations":["property_evaluation"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Forbid rules flag matching lines","Require rules flag missing patterns"],"references":["PMAT-225: PROPERTY-DSL Sprint 12","docs/specifications/world-class-bash-linter-spec.md"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":11,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"property-dsl-v1 Property definition DSL contract (PMAT-225). Verifies that bashrs property --custom loads user-defined property checks from TOML files. The DSL supports forbid rules (regex patterns that are violations when matched) and require rules (patterns that must match at least one line). Custom properties integrate with built-in properties in both terminal and JSON output. property_evaluation eval_property(script, property_def) -> {pass, fail} with violations Forbid rules flag matching lines Require rules flag missing patterns Forbid rules flag matching lines Forbid rules flag matching lines Require rules flag missing patterns Require rules flag missing patterns PMAT-225: PROPERTY-DSL Sprint 12 docs/specifications/world-class-bash-linter-spec.md"},{"stem":"property-invariants-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/property-invariants-v1.yaml","description":"Universal (∀-quantified) invariants verified by property-based testing. Each property is tested across 256+ random inputs via proptest. A single counterexample falsifies the claim. Stronger than example-based tests because the input space is explored stochastically.","equations":["invariant_checking"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Idempotency checks detect missing -p/-f flags","Determinism checks detect $RANDOM, $$, date"],"references":["GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts","proptest crate: Hypothesis-style property testing for Rust"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":13,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"property-invariants-v1 Universal (∀-quantified) invariants verified by property-based testing. Each property is tested across 256+ random inputs via proptest. A single counterexample falsifies the claim. Stronger than example-based tests because the input space is explored stochastically. invariant_checking check(script, invariant) -> bool for invariant in {idempotency, determinism, posix, safety} Idempotency checks detect missing -p/-f flags Determinism checks detect $RANDOM, $$, date Idempotency checks detect missing -p/-f flags Idempotency checks detect missing -p/-f flags Determinism checks detect $RANDOM, $$, date Determinism checks detect $RANDOM, $$, date GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts proptest crate: Hypothesis-style property testing for Rust"},{"stem":"purification-pipeline-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/purification-pipeline-v1.yaml","description":"Provable purification contracts (GH-183). The bash purifier transforms non-deterministic bash into safe, idempotent POSIX sh. Each invariant is falsifiable — a single counterexample breaks the contract.","equations":["purification"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Purified output passes shellcheck -s sh","All $RANDOM/timestamps removed","Operations made idempotent with -p/-f flags"],"references":["GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts","CLAUDE.md: Workflow 1 — Bash → Purified Bash (PRIMARY)"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":3,"falsification_count":10,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"purification-pipeline-v1 Provable purification contracts (GH-183). The bash purifier transforms non-deterministic bash into safe, idempotent POSIX sh. Each invariant is falsifiable — a single counterexample breaks the contract. purification purify(bash_script) -> posix_script where is_deterministic(posix_script) AND is_idempotent(posix_script) Purified output passes shellcheck -s sh All $RANDOM/timestamps removed Operations made idempotent with -p/-f flags Purified output passes shellcheck -s sh Purified output passes shellcheck -s sh All $RANDOM/timestamps removed All $RANDOM/timestamps removed Operations made idempotent with -p/-f flags Operations made idempotent with -p/-f flags GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts CLAUDE.md: Workflow 1 — Bash → Purified Bash (PRIMARY)"},{"stem":"qwen3-4b-qlora-training-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/qwen3-4b-qlora-training-v1.yaml","description":"Qwen3-4B NF4 QLoRA training contract for Shell Safety Classifier chat model.\nRun 7: First true LoRA training after ENT-LoRA-001..018 implementation.\nUpgraded from Qwen2.5-Coder-0.5B (6 failed full-FT runs, max 32% accuracy)\nto Qwen3-4B (8x capacity, NF4 quantized base, LoRA adapters on Q/V/O/Gate).\nBinary classification + explanation + fix suggestions for shell scripts.\n","equations":["lora_forward","nf4_quantization","qlora_gradient"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant","bound","postcondition"],"properties":["Base weight freezing","LoRA gradient flow","Loss decreases","PEFT format compliance"],"references":["Hu et al. (2021) LoRA: Low-Rank Adaptation of Large Language Models (arXiv:2106.09685)","Dettmers et al. (2023) QLoRA: Efficient Finetuning of Quantized LLMs (arXiv:2305.14314)"],"depends_on":["chat-model-training-v1","shellsafetybench-v1"],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":4,"falsification_count":10,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"qwen3-4b-qlora-training-v1 Qwen3-4B NF4 QLoRA training contract for Shell Safety Classifier chat model.\nRun 7: First true LoRA training after ENT-LoRA-001..018 implementation.\nUpgraded from Qwen2.5-Coder-0.5B (6 failed full-FT runs, max 32% accuracy)\nto Qwen3-4B (8x capacity, NF4 quantized base, LoRA adapters on Q/V/O/Gate).\nBinary classification + explanation + fix suggestions for shell scripts.\n lora_forward h = W_nf4 @ x + (alpha / rank) * B @ A @ x Base weights W_nf4 are frozen (quantized, no gradient updates) Only A and B matrices receive gradients rank=16 << min(d_in, d_out) ensures low-rank bottleneck Scaling factor alpha/rank = 32/16 = 2.0 nf4_quantization W_nf4 = quantize_nf4(W_bf16, block_size=64) Block size = 64 elements per quantization group NF4 uses information-theoretically optimal 4-bit data type for normally distributed weights Quantization is applied once at model load, not during training Dequantization for forward pass: W_approx = dequantize_nf4(W_nf4) qlora_gradient dL/dA = B^T @ (dL/dh) @ x^T ; dL/dB = (dL/dh) @ (A @ x)^T Gradients flow through B and A only (base weights frozen) Chain rule applied through the low-rank decomposition No gradient computation for W_nf4 (saves memory) Base weight freezing W_nf4[layer][module] is bit-identical before and after any training step LoRA gradient flow For each LoRA module: requires_grad(A) == true AND requires_grad(B) == true Loss decreases E[L(step_t)] < E[L(step_{t-k})] for k >= 100 (moving average) PEFT format compliance adapter_config.json has keys: r, lora_alpha, target_modules, task_type, base_model_name_or_path Hu et al. (2021) LoRA: Low-Rank Adaptation of Large Language Models (arXiv:2106.09685) Dettmers et al. (2023) QLoRA: Efficient Finetuning of Quantized LLMs (arXiv:2305.14314)"},{"stem":"shellsafetybench-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/shellsafetybench-v1.yaml","description":"ShellSafetyBench pipeline contract (v12).\nVerifies CWE mapping, benchmark export schema, conversation quality,\nand eval harness correctness.","equations":["benchmark_validity"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["No exact duplicates between train and test","Class balance within acceptable range"],"references":["docs/specifications/shell-safety-inference.md Section 14"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":11,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"shellsafetybench-v1 ShellSafetyBench pipeline contract (v12).\nVerifies CWE mapping, benchmark export schema, conversation quality,\nand eval harness correctness. benchmark_validity forall split in {train, val, test}: class_balance(split) in [15%, 85%] AND no_duplicates(train, test) No exact duplicates between train and test Class balance within acceptable range No exact duplicates between train and test No exact duplicates between train and test Class balance within acceptable range Class balance within acceptable range docs/specifications/shell-safety-inference.md Section 14"},{"stem":"test-gen-ext-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/test-gen-ext-v1.yaml","description":"Test generation extension contract (PMAT-223). Verifies that bashrs test --generate emits property test stubs (idempotency, determinism, POSIX, safety) and integration test stubs (exit codes, output validation, environment isolation) via the --generate-type flag with values: unit (default), property, integration, all.","equations":["test_generation"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Generated tests are syntactically valid BATS","Property tests check idempotency and determinism"],"references":["PMAT-223: TEST-GEN-EXT Sprint 9","docs/specifications/unified-testing-quality-spec.md"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":11,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"test-gen-ext-v1 Test generation extension contract (PMAT-223). Verifies that bashrs test --generate emits property test stubs (idempotency, determinism, POSIX, safety) and integration test stubs (exit codes, output validation, environment isolation) via the --generate-type flag with values: unit (default), property, integration, all. test_generation generate(script, type) -> test_suite where type in {unit, property, integration} Generated tests are syntactically valid BATS Property tests check idempotency and determinism Generated tests are syntactically valid BATS Generated tests are syntactically valid BATS Property tests check idempotency and determinism Property tests check idempotency and determinism PMAT-223: TEST-GEN-EXT Sprint 9 docs/specifications/unified-testing-quality-spec.md"},{"stem":"transpiler-core-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/transpiler-core-v1.yaml","description":"Core transpiler invariants (GH-183). Every Rust→Shell transpilation must satisfy: determinism, POSIX structure, variable safety, and selective stdlib emission. These are falsifiable — a single counterexample breaks the contract.","equations":["transpilation"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Output passes shellcheck -s sh","Same input produces identical output (deterministic)"],"references":["GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts","GH-148: rash transpiler stdlib"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":11,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"transpiler-core-v1 Core transpiler invariants (GH-183). Every Rust→Shell transpilation must satisfy: determinism, POSIX structure, variable safety, and selective stdlib emission. These are falsifiable — a single counterexample breaks the contract. transpilation transpile(rust_ast) -> shell_script where shellcheck(shell_script) == PASS Output passes shellcheck -s sh Same input produces identical output (deterministic) Output passes shellcheck -s sh Output passes shellcheck -s sh Same input produces identical output (deterministic) Same input produces identical output (deterministic) GH-183: KZ-11 Missing provable contracts GH-148: rash transpiler stdlib"},{"stem":"transpiler-stdlib-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/transpiler-stdlib-v1.yaml","description":"Transpiler stdlib functions (GH-148) produce correct POSIX shell output. capture() → $(...), exit() → exit N, sleep() → sleep N.","equations":["stdlib_mapping"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["All mapped functions produce equivalent behavior","Unmapped functions produce clear error"],"references":["GH-148: rash transpiler missing stdlib for real-world shell scripts"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":18,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"transpiler-stdlib-v1 Transpiler stdlib functions (GH-148) produce correct POSIX shell output. capture() → $(...), exit() → exit N, sleep() → sleep N. stdlib_mapping map_stdlib(rust_fn) -> shell_equivalent where behavior(rust_fn) ~= behavior(shell_equivalent) All mapped functions produce equivalent behavior Unmapped functions produce clear error All mapped functions produce equivalent behavior All mapped functions produce equivalent behavior Unmapped functions produce clear error Unmapped functions produce clear error GH-148: rash transpiler missing stdlib for real-world shell scripts"},{"stem":"wasm-codebert-encoder-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/wasm-codebert-encoder-v1.yaml","description":"Pure-Rust CodeBERT encoder for WASM inference. Implements the full\nRoBERTa transformer encoder (12 layers, 768-dim, 12 heads) using\nonly f32 operations. Loads int8 SafeTensors weights.\n\nKill criterion 5 triggered: 2681ms native CPU for 33 tokens.\nEstimated WASM performance: 5-13 seconds (2-5x slowdown).\nThreshold: 2000ms. Decision: Ship CLI only.","equations":["wasm_encoding"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["WASM and native produce equivalent embeddings","Inference time < 5s in browser"],"references":["Devlin et al. (2019) BERT","docs/specifications/shell-safety-inference.md"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":2,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"wasm-codebert-encoder-v1 Pure-Rust CodeBERT encoder for WASM inference. Implements the full\nRoBERTa transformer encoder (12 layers, 768-dim, 12 heads) using\nonly f32 operations. Loads int8 SafeTensors weights.\n\nKill criterion 5 triggered: 2681ms native CPU for 33 tokens.\nEstimated WASM performance: 5-13 seconds (2-5x slowdown).\nThreshold: 2000ms. Decision: Ship CLI only. wasm_encoding encode_wasm(tokens) ~= encode_native(tokens) within tolerance WASM and native produce equivalent embeddings Inference time < 5s in browser WASM and native produce equivalent embeddings WASM and native produce equivalent embeddings Inference time < 5s in browser Inference time < 5s in browser Devlin et al. (2019) BERT docs/specifications/shell-safety-inference.md"},{"stem":"wasm-linter-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/wasm-linter-v1.yaml","description":"bashrs-wasm WASM linter bindings contract.\nVerifies that the WASM API surface produces correct JSON output\nfor shell/makefile/dockerfile linting and classification.","equations":["wasm_api"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["All functions return valid JSON (never panic)","WASM binary size < 5MB"],"references":["docs/specifications/shell-safety-inference.md Section 8.3"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":6,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"wasm-linter-v1 bashrs-wasm WASM linter bindings contract.\nVerifies that the WASM API surface produces correct JSON output\nfor shell/makefile/dockerfile linting and classification. wasm_api lint_wasm(script, fmt) -> JSON where fmt in {shell, makefile, dockerfile} All functions return valid JSON (never panic) WASM binary size < 5MB All functions return valid JSON (never panic) All functions return valid JSON (never panic) WASM binary size < 5MB WASM binary size < 5MB docs/specifications/shell-safety-inference.md Section 8.3"},{"stem":"wgpu-training-v1","path":"provable-contracts/contracts/wgpu-training-v1.yaml","description":"Provable contract for WGPU-based transformer training on AMD GPUs. Validates backward pass correctness, NF4 dequant parity, checkpoint round-trip, and real data convergence. Enables training on non-NVIDIA hardware (AMD W5700X via Vulkan).","equations":["gpu_training"],"obligation_types":["invariant","invariant"],"properties":["Loss decreases over training steps","Gradient norms bounded"],"references":["trueno WGPU backward: src/backends/gpu/device/backward.rs","entrenar WGPU trainer: src/train/transformer_trainer/wgpu_trainer.rs","entrenar WGPU checkpoint: src/train/transformer_trainer/wgpu_checkpoint.rs"],"depends_on":[],"is_registry":false,"kind":"kernel","obligation_count":2,"falsification_count":6,"kani_count":1,"corpus_text":"wgpu-training-v1 Provable contract for WGPU-based transformer training on AMD GPUs. Validates backward pass correctness, NF4 dequant parity, checkpoint round-trip, and real data convergence. Enables training on non-NVIDIA hardware (AMD W5700X via Vulkan). gpu_training train(model, data, lr) -> model' where loss(model') < loss(model) Loss decreases over training steps Gradient norms bounded Loss decreases over training steps Loss decreases over training steps Gradient norms bounded Gradient norms bounded trueno WGPU backward: src/backends/gpu/device/backward.rs entrenar WGPU trainer: src/train/transformer_trainer/wgpu_trainer.rs entrenar WGPU checkpoint: src/train/transformer_trainer/wgpu_checkpoint.rs"}],"score_cache":{"property-invariants-v1":0.525,"bidirectional-attention-v1":0.5291666666666667,"mcdc-coverage-v1":0.525,"encoder-roundtrip-v1":0.525,"parser-soundness-v1":0.525,"dimension-independent-kernels-v1":0.525,"linter-docker-make-v1":0.525,"nf4-cublas-parity-v2":0.525,"chat-inference-pipeline-v1":0.475,"cpu-gpu-forward-parity-v1":0.5025000000000001,"encoder-forward-v1":0.5291666666666667,"lint-perf-v1":0.525,"purification-pipeline-v1":0.49166666666666664,"benchmark-expansion-v1":0.525,"backward-cache-key-v1":0.525,"linear-probe-classifier-v1":0.5166666666666666,"test-gen-ext-v1":0.525,"wasm-codebert-encoder-v1":0.525,"linter-security-rules-v1":0.525,"linter-coverage-v1":0.525,"hf-publish-v1":0.525,"nf4-cublas-throughput-v1":0.525,"probar-shell-safety-v1":0.525,"qwen3-4b-qlora-training-v1":0.5125000000000001,"transpiler-stdlib-v1":0.525,"wasm-linter-v1":0.525,"wgpu-training-v1":0.525,"linter-det-idem-v1":0.525,"nf4-codebook-parity-v1":0.525,"property-dsl-v1":0.525,"transpiler-core-v1":0.525,"chat-model-training-v1":0.5041666666666667,"shellsafetybench-v1":0.525,"learned-position-embedding-v1":0.5625},"pagerank_cache":{"linear-probe-classifier-v1":0.016114259122802257,"w